<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11546&amp;p=132696#p132696"><![CDATA[
Based on my experience I would recommend getting to know what kind of campus it is, and how everything involved will develop you as a person rather then how it would land you a job. I would especially learn first what kind of work each of the professors do, and match up your classes from that.<br />Additionally if you go for 3D, do not forgo basic 2D composition lessons such as shape, color, and balance.<br /><br />If you do well enough, the professors might take the effort to find you artistic job opportunity (at least mine tried). Otherwise be content with whatever you can do for money, and if you truly are an artist you'll never stop doing art even with a ordinary minimum wage job.<br /><br />side note: If the content of your post is a question, don't make the title of it a statement.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6385">43110</a> — Mon Aug 18, 2014 8:27 am</p><hr />
